# Testing

## Running Tests

Always use the project virtual environment to run tests:

```bash
.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/ -v                       # all tests, verbose
.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/test_leads.py -v           # single test file
.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/test_leads.py::test_create_lead -v  # single test
.venv/bin/python -m pytest -x -v                            # stop on first failure
.venv/bin/python -m pytest -k "test_create" -v              # filter by name
.venv/bin/python -m pytest --cov=app -v                     # with coverage
```

Do NOT use bare `pytest` — the system Python may lack project dependencies.

After making code changes, always run the relevant test file(s) and verify all tests pass before considering the task complete.

## Structure

- Mirror the `app/` layout: `tests/test_leads.py`, `tests/test_auth.py`, `tests/test_admin.py`
- Prefix test files with `test_` and test functions with `test_`
- Use fixtures from `tests/conftest.py` for shared setup (db sessions, test client, auth tokens)

## Fixtures

Key fixtures defined in `tests/conftest.py`:
- `db_session` — async SQLite in-memory session (tables created/dropped per test)
- `client` — `httpx.AsyncClient` with dependency overrides for the test db
- `admin_token` — JWT for the first registered user (admin)
- `auth_token` — JWT for a second registered user (attorney)

## Conventions

- Test both success and error paths
- Verify status codes, response bodies, and side effects
- Use `@pytest.mark.parametrize` for testing multiple inputs (e.g. valid/invalid emails)
- For file uploads, use `httpx` multipart: `files=[("resume", ("name.pdf", content, "application/pdf"))]`
- Use helper functions (e.g. `_resume_file()`, `_valid_lead_data()`) to reduce boilerplate
